574
00:25:26,926 --> 00:25:28,392
Thank you, Dr. Grey.

575
00:25:28,460 --> 00:25:31,311
It's your witness, Ms. Gamble.

576
00:25:31,379 --> 00:25:35,199
You mentioned that Sofia is
at your house today, Dr. Grey.

577
00:25:35,267 --> 00:25:37,696
She is. It must be nice
for you and Dr. Torres

578
00:25:37,720 --> 00:25:39,114
to have daughters
around the same age.

579
00:25:39,138 --> 00:25:41,316
And they get along,
right? It is very nice.

580
00:25:41,340 --> 00:25:43,274
They love playing together.

581
00:25:43,326 --> 00:25:45,270
So, who's watching your daughters
right now while you're here?

582
00:25:45,294 --> 00:25:47,428
Their Aunt Amelia.

583
00:25:47,496 --> 00:25:50,896
You recently lost your
husband. Is that correct?

584
00:25:52,384 --> 00:25:53,917
I did.

585
00:25:53,985 --> 00:25:55,919
My sincerest condolences.

586
00:25:55,987 --> 00:25:58,038
Thank you.

587
00:25:58,107 --> 00:26:01,191
So, you're a single parent.

588
00:26:01,260 --> 00:26:03,861
I am. And Callie's
a single parent.

589
00:26:06,064 --> 00:26:07,304
Is that a question, or...

590
00:26:07,350 --> 00:26:09,883
So you two must help
each other out a lot.

591
00:26:09,951 --> 00:26:11,162
Two single parents.

592
00:26:11,186 --> 00:26:13,231
Callie drops Sofia off
at your place sometimes

593
00:26:13,255 --> 00:26:15,100
when she has to work
or when she has plans

594
00:26:15,124 --> 00:26:18,058
or when she needs
a night off. Correct?

595
00:26:18,126 --> 00:26:19,309
A "night off"?

596
00:26:20,646 --> 00:26:22,512
Being a mom isn't a job.

597
00:26:22,581 --> 00:26:24,301
We don't punch in and punch out.

598
00:26:24,666 --> 00:26:26,099
There are no nights off.

599
00:26:26,168 --> 00:26:27,668
We are both single parents.

600
00:26:27,736 --> 00:26:29,419
That's not a dirty word.

601
00:26:29,488 --> 00:26:32,656
But we do need help getting
our kids to where they need to be

602
00:26:32,724 --> 00:26:34,485
with all of their limbs intact.

603
00:26:34,509 --> 00:26:36,327
So we lean on each other.

604
00:26:36,395 --> 00:26:38,796
That's not a sign of
weakness or bad parenting,

605
00:26:38,864 --> 00:26:40,464
if that's where
you're going with this.

606
00:26:40,516 --> 00:26:44,017
It takes a village,
and we have a village.

607
00:26:44,086 --> 00:26:45,869
Here in Seattle. What?

608
00:26:45,938 --> 00:26:47,382
The village you
just mentioned...

609
00:26:47,406 --> 00:26:49,807
The seamless support
system these mothers built,

610
00:26:49,875 --> 00:26:51,442
this essential network.

611
00:26:51,510 --> 00:26:53,644
It's all here in Seattle.

612
00:26:53,712 --> 00:26:56,241
Sofia's friends and her
school, her teachers...

613
00:26:56,265 --> 00:26:59,066
Her home is here in Seattle.

614
00:26:59,134 --> 00:27:02,369
That's what Sofia
would be leaving.

615
00:27:02,438 --> 00:27:03,482
Is that what you're saying?

616
00:27:03,506 --> 00:27:05,221
No. I was saying...

617
00:27:05,291 --> 00:27:07,574
No further questions,
Your Honor.

618
00:27:14,300 --> 00:27:17,601
Dr. Robbins was already
a brilliant pediatric surgeon,

619
00:27:17,669 --> 00:27:20,036
but since she's
completed her fellowship,

620
00:27:20,105 --> 00:27:21,572
I've watched her turn into

621
00:27:21,640 --> 00:27:23,990
one of the most renowned
fetal surgeons in the country.

622
00:27:24,059 --> 00:27:26,710
A child would be lucky to
have her as a role model parent.

623
00:27:28,396 --> 00:27:30,476
No further questions,
Your Honor.

